    <!-- QUICK ANSWER -->
    <div class="quick-answer">
      <div class="qa-label">Quick Answer</div>
      <p>160g of protein in a day looks like: <strong>3 eggs + Greek yogurt at breakfast (40g)</strong>, a large chicken breast at lunch (50g), a protein shake mid-afternoon (25g), and ground beef or salmon at dinner (45g). One high-protein anchor at every meal — no extreme eating, no skipping.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- STAT BOXES -->
    <div class="stat-row">
      <div class="stat-box">
        <div class="stat-num">160g</div>
        <div class="stat-label">daily protein target for active recomposition</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-box">
        <div class="stat-num">40g</div>
        <div class="stat-label">average per meal across 4 eating occasions</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-box">
        <div class="stat-num">+40g</div>
        <div class="stat-label">above the 120g baseline — roughly one extra serving</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>If you've already seen <a href="/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/">what a 120g protein day looks like</a>, you know the baseline — three solid meals, each anchored by a real protein source, gets most men close. 120g is the number that stops muscle loss in its tracks after 40.</p>

    <p>But 160g is a different goal. This is the number for men who aren't just trying to preserve what they have — they're actively trying to rebuild. Lose the gut. Add lean mass back. Do what the fitness industry calls "body recomposition," which is the polite way of saying: get stronger and leaner at the same time.</p>

    <p>The difference between 120g and 160g is roughly one extra serving of protein per day. But knowing that in theory and knowing what it actually looks like on a plate are two different things.</p>

    <div class="killer-line">
      120g protects your muscle.<br><span>160g rebuilds it.</span>
    </div>

    <h2>120g vs 160g: Understanding the Two Targets</h2>

    <div class="target-compare">
      <div class="target-card">
        <div class="tc-label">Baseline Target</div>
        <div class="tc-num">120g</div>
        <div class="tc-goal">Muscle Preservation</div>
        <div class="tc-desc">The maintenance floor for most men over 40. Prevents the gradual muscle loss that starts in your 40s and accelerates through your 50s.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="target-card highlight">
        <div class="tc-label">Recomposition Target</div>
        <div class="tc-num">160g</div>
        <div class="tc-goal">Muscle Rebuilding</div>
        <div class="tc-desc">The active target for men pursuing lean mass gain while reducing body fat. Requires one additional high-protein serving per day above the baseline.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>Which target is right for you depends on your goal. If you're focused on staying strong and healthy as you age, 120g is a completely legitimate and meaningful target. If you're training consistently and want to actively change your body composition — get leaner while getting stronger — 160g is the number to aim for.</p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <p><strong>A note on body weight:</strong> These are general targets for men in the 160–190 pound range. If you're significantly heavier or lighter, your target shifts proportionally. The underlying principle — roughly 0.8–1g per pound of bodyweight — stays the same.</p>
    </div>

