    <h2>Can You Hit 160g Without Protein Supplements?</h2>

    <p>Technically yes — but it's tight. A full day of whole food sources can get you there if every meal is built around a serious protein anchor. The problem is meal size. To hit 160g from food alone, you're eating large portions at every sitting, which can feel like a second job when you're not hungry.</p>

    <p>One protein shake per day makes 160g consistently achievable without forcing food. It adds 25g without adding much volume or effort — and for most men, that's the difference between hitting the number most days versus barely clearing it on good days.</p>

    <p>The goal isn't perfection. The goal is consistently clearing 160g more days than not.</p>

    <h2>Why Tracking Matters More at 160g Than at 120g</h2>

    <p>At 120g, experienced eaters can often get close by feel. Three solid protein meals and you're in the range. The margin for error is forgiving.</p>

    <p>At 160g, feel doesn't work as well. You need to know your running total by mid-day, because if you're sitting at 60g by 2pm, you know dinner needs to be a serious protein meal. If you're at 90g, you have more flexibility.</p>

    <p>This is where a simple tracking habit earns its keep. Not a full macro app with calories and carbs — just your protein number, updated once or twice per day, so you always know where you stand.</p>

    <div class="author-note">
      <div class="an-label">A Note From Robert</div>
      <p>I spent a long time eating what felt like a lot of protein and wondering why I wasn't seeing the results I expected. The problem wasn't the food — it was that I had no idea what my actual number was at the end of the day. Some days were great. Some days I'd realize at 9pm I'd barely hit 90g. You can't manage what you can't see. Once I started tracking just protein — nothing else, just that one number — the pattern became obvious, and the results followed.</p>
    </div>

